# Cursor Rules — Multi-Source Candidate Data Transformer

Before doing anything in this repo, read `PROJECT_CONTEXT.md` at the repo root in full.
It is the authoritative spec for architecture, stack, scope, and what is explicitly
out of scope. Treat it as binding, not as a suggestion.

## Operating rules for this session

1. Work one pipeline stage at a time. Do not implement multiple stages in a single
   response unless explicitly asked to. After implementing a stage, stop and summarize
   what you built and why, in plain language, before moving on.
2. Do not introduce new libraries, frameworks, or architectural patterns beyond what's
   listed in PROJECT_CONTEXT.md without flagging it first and explaining why the
   existing plan is insufficient.
3. Do not silently "improve" or expand scope (e.g. adding a third source, adding
   retries/caching/queueing, adding abstraction layers for hypothetical future needs).
   If you think something should be added, say so and wait for confirmation.
4. Every function should be small enough and clear enough that its author could
   explain it in one or two sentences in a live recorded demo. If a piece of logic is
   getting complex, prefer splitting it into named helper functions with clear
   responsibilities over one dense function.
5. Never fabricate or default a field value to make output look more complete than
   the source data supports. Missing data becomes `null`/empty, never invented.
6. When normalizing or merging, prefer explicit, readable logic (lookup tables,
   ordered precedence arrays, named constants) over clever one-liners or deeply
   nested conditionals.
7. After each stage works, remind the user to commit with a clear message describing
   what stage was completed (e.g. `git commit -m "Implement normalize stage: phone, date, country, skills"`).
   Don't commit automatically — let the user review the diff first.
